        <h3>Foundation Software — Best for AP-level waiver compliance</h3>
        <p>Foundation Software integrates lien waiver collection directly into accounts payable. You can require a current lien waiver before a check is released to a subcontractor — the system will alert you if a required waiver is missing or if a subcontractor's certificate of insurance has expired. For mid-size contractors with active AP departments, this payables-integrated compliance is valuable.</p>

        <h3>Sage 100 Contractor — Similar AP-integrated tracking</h3>
        <p>Like Foundation, Sage 100 Contractor ties subcontractor compliance (lien waivers, insurance certificates) to the AP payment process. You can configure the system to require valid documentation before a payment can be processed, creating a compliance checkpoint in the normal workflow.</p>

        <h3>Knowify — For subcontractors managing their own waivers</h3>
        <p>From the subcontractor side, Knowify helps you track when you've submitted lien waivers with each pay application — and ensures the waiver amount matches your billing. If you're a sub who needs to provide waivers to GCs as part of the billing cycle, Knowify's pay application workflow keeps this organized.</p>

        <h3>Dedicated lien waiver platforms</h3>
        <p>Several standalone platforms specialize in lien waiver collection and compliance, often used alongside (rather than replacing) project management software:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Lien Waiver Hub:</strong> Cloud-based lien waiver management with e-signature, state-specific form templates, and tracking dashboard</li>
          <li><strong>Traction:</strong> Compliance-focused platform for managing lien waivers and supplier compliance documentation</li>
          <li><strong>DocuSign CLM:</strong> General e-signature platform used by some contractors for lien waiver collection</li>
          <li><strong>Levelset (by Procore):</strong> Dedicated lien rights and waiver management platform with notice-to-owner filing, lien waiver exchange, and payment dispute tools. Particularly strong for complex multi-party projects with GC, sub, and supplier waiver chains.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>What to look for in software lien waiver features</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>State-specific form templates:</strong> Lien waiver requirements vary by state; software should use the correct forms</li>
          <li><strong>Conditional vs. unconditional tracking:</strong> The platform should distinguish between waiver types and track amounts</li>
          <li><strong>Payment hold integration:</strong> Ability to require a waiver before releasing payment — not just as a document storage location</li>
          <li><strong>E-signature:</strong> Reduces friction in collecting signed waivers from subs</li>
          <li><strong>Audit trail:</strong> Document when waivers were submitted, signed, and tied to which payment</li>
          <li><strong>Supplier-level tracking:</strong> GCs often need waivers from material suppliers in addition to subcontractors</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>The practical approach for smaller contractors</h2>
        <p>For smaller GCs who don't use enterprise platforms with built-in waiver tracking, a practical minimum approach:</p>
        <ol>
          <li>Create a Google Sheet or simple tracker with one row per sub per project, showing waiver type required, date submitted, amount, and date paid</li>
          <li>Download state-specific lien waiver forms (many state bar associations publish these) and save them in your document template library</li>
          <li>Require a signed waiver before issuing payment — make this a standard process, not an afterthought</li>
          <li>Store signed waivers in a job folder organized by project (job file in Buildertrend, Dropbox, or wherever your job documents live)</li>
        </ol>
        <p>This isn't as automated as integrated software, but it's dramatically better than no system at all. As you grow, the integration in a full platform pays for itself in reduced liability exposure.</p>

